{
  "doc_id": "25537",
  "text": "Cell cycle deregulation is often a target for cancer progression, especially the shortening of the G 1 interval of the cell cycle. Importantly, in HTLV-1 infected cells, Tax has been shown to increase cyclin D2 as well as p21/waf1 expression at the transcriptional level [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . This is an unusual circumstance in light of the fact that p21/waf1 is traditionally thought of as an inhibitor of cell cycle progression. An alternative explanation is that p21/waf1 acts as an assembly factor of cyclin D2/cdk associated complexes in HTLV-1 infected cells. This particular function appears to be p21/waf1's role in forming stable and active kinase complexes, which in turn could function to shorten the G 1 phase in HTLV-1 infected cells. It has previously been shown that the HTLV-1 Tax protein shortens the G 1 phase of the cell cycle [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Therefore, transactivation of p21/waf1 by Tax could contribute to this effect.",
